Bagging and Random Forests: spam data

Import data

#Load the data and split into training and test sets.
rm(list=ls())
spam <- read.csv("SPAM.csv",header=T)
spam$spam = as.factor(ifelse(spam$spam==T,"spam","email"))
train = spam[!spam$testid, -2]
test.y = spam[spam$testid,1]
test = spam[spam$testid, -c(1,2)]
n = nrow(train)
m = nrow(test)

caret: cross-validation settings

library("caret")

cv <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",
  number = 10,
  allowParallel = TRUE
)

Models

tree <- train(
  spam ~ ., train,
  method = "rpart2",
  tuneLength = 9,
  trControl=cv)
plot(tree)

rf <- train(
  spam~., train,
  ntree = 50,
  method = "rf",
  trControl=cv)
rf
## Random Forest 
## 
## 3065 samples
##   57 predictor
##    2 classes: 'email', 'spam' 
## 
## No pre-processing
## Resampling: Cross-Validated (10 fold) 
## Summary of sample sizes: 2758, 2759, 2758, 2759, 2758, 2758, ... 
## Resampling results across tuning parameters:
## 
##   mtry  Accuracy   Kappa    
##    2    0.9422633  0.8782168
##   29    0.9399789  0.8739767
##   57    0.9367184  0.8669007
## 
## Accuracy was used to select the optimal model using  the largest value.
## The final value used for the model was mtry = 2.
plot(rf)

plot(varImp(rf))

Cross-validation Accuracy

models = list(
    tree=tree,
    rf=rf
  )

resamps = resamples(models)
bwplot(resamps, metric = "Accuracy")

Test Accuracy
